We can calculate the <b><span style="color: #4257B2">annual coupon payment</span></b> by using the following formula:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Coupon payment} =\text{Face Value} \cdot  \frac{\text{Annual Coupon Rate}}{\text{Payments per year}}
\end{aligned}$$

Considering that our bond pays annually (once per year), we can simplify the above formula to:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Coupon payment} =\text{Face Value} \cdot  \text{Annual Coupon Rate}
\end{aligned}$$

Given the face value of $2,000 and the coupon rate of 5.7%, the <b><span style="color: #4257B2">annual coupon payment </span></b> is:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Coupon payment} &=\$2,000 \cdot  5.7\% \\[10pt]
&= 0.057 \cdot \$2,000 \\[10pt]
&= \$114 \tag{2}
\end{aligned}$$

By inputting the values of the annual coupon payment (Eq. 2) and the current market price (Eq.3) into Eq.1, we get the value of the <b><span style="color: #4257B2">current yield</span></b>:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Current Yield} &= \frac{\$114}{ \$2,179.2} \\[10pt]
&= \boxed{5.23\%}
\end{aligned}$$

Next,  we need to calculate <b><span style="color: #4257B2">the  yield to maturity</span></b>.

The <b><span style="color: #4257B2">yield to maturity </span></b> is the rate of return for a bond assuming that the investor holds the bond until its maturity date. 

To calculate <b><span style="color: #4257B2">the yield to maturity</span></b>, we can use the below formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Yield to maturity} = \frac{ \text{Coupon Payment} + \frac{\text{Face Value} - \text{Current Price}}{\text{Number Of Compounding Periods}} }{\frac{\text{Face Value} - \text{Current Price}}{2}}
\end{aligned}
